{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "Second Scholasticism greatly developed the medieval theory of continuous quantity as the Aristotelian notion for thematizing spatial extension, paving the way for the idea of space as extension in early modern natural philosophy.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "The article analyzes the section related to the category of continuous quantity in the Coimbra commentary on the Dialectics (1606), showing that it is indebted to the novel theory of Francisco Suárez on quantity as bestowing extension to a body in a particular sense, something which had been overlooked by previous research.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "The scholarly debate on quantity was brought to China, and here the Chinese translation is examined of the section on quantity in the fourth volume of the Mingli Tan, published in China in 1636-1639.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "Among Aristotle's ten categories, poson (quantity) is of particular importance, being discussed in Chapter 6 of Categories, just after ousia (substance).",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "As is known, in Cat. 4b 20-5a 35, Aristotle distinguishes quantity into discrete (διωρισμένον) and continuous (συνέχες) quantity.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "Continuous quantities \"are composed of parts which have a position in relation to one another\"; they are \"lines, surfaces, bodies\", thus extended beings, \"and also, besides these, time and place\".",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "Thomistic philosophy developed over the centuries what has been called (in opposition to Ockham's thesis of the identity of quantity and material substance) 'quantity realism'.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "Thomists understood the category of quantity as a res distinct from the material substance, the study of which pertained both to logicians and metaphysicians.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "Such a realistic conception of continuous quantity as extension became not only because of the foreign-sounding language, but also because the Chinese reader has little background understanding that could help him appreciate the relevance of the questions being addressed.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "Unlike the Jihe yuanben which exerts until today a considerable influence in China, the Mingli tan and Aristotelian logic in general have failed to attract the interest of the Chinese.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "But despite its lack of reception in China, the Mingli tan still deserves scholarly attention.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "As we have shown here, it introduced a very sophisticated notion of quantity, not only based on Aristotle's Categories, but also incorporating important philosophical ideas from Thomism, Scotism, and Nominalism, including the most recent developments at that time on quantity as extension, by the leading scholastic philosopher, Francisco Suárez.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
